.1-.06-.07-.12.03-.12h3.89a.29.29 0 0 0 .26-.19l1.2-3.52z"></path></svg></p></a></span></div></div><div class="n ix iy iz ja jb jc jd je jf"><div class="n o"><div class="jg s"><div class="ca" aria-hidden="false" aria-describedby="postFooterSocialMenu" aria-labelledby="postFooterSocialMenu"><div><div class="ca" role="tooltip" aria-hidden="false"><button class="el em ce cf cg ch ci cj ck bq en eo cl ep eq" aria-controls="postFooterSocialMenu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Share Post"><svg width="25" height="25" class="r"><g fill-rule="evenodd"><path d="M15.6 5a.42.42 0 0 0 .17-.3.42.42 0 0 0-.12-.33l-2.8-2.79a.5.5 0 0 0-.7 0l-2.8 2.8a.4.4 0 0 0-.1.32c0 .12.07.23.16.3h.02a.45.45 0 0 0 .57-.04l2-2V10c0 .28.23.5.5.5s.5-.22.5-.5V2.93l2.02 2.02c.08.07.18.12.3.13.11.01.21-.02.3-.08v.01"></path><path d="M18 7h-1.5a.5.5 0 0 0 0 1h1.6c.5 0 .9.4.9.9v10.2c0 .5-.4.9-.9.9H6.9a.9.9 0 0 1-.9-.9V8.9c0-.5.4-.9.9-.9h1.6a.5.5 0 0 0 .35-.15A.5.5 0 0 0 9 7.5a.5.5 0 0 0-.15-.35A.5.5 0 0 0 8.5 7H7a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v10c0 1.1.9 2 2 2h11a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V9a2 2 0 0 0-2-2"></path></g></svg></button></div></div></div></div><div class="jh s"><span><a href="https://medium.com/m/signin?actionUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2F_%2Fbookmark%2Fp%2Fb7c347d74351&amp;operation=register&amp;redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fuxdesign.cc%2Fthe-13-scientific-principles-every-uxer-needs-to-know-b7c347d74351&amp;source=post_actions_header--------------------------bookmark_preview-----------" class="el em ce cf cg ch ci cj ck bq en eo cl ep eq" rel="noopener"><svg width="25" height="25" viewBox="0 0 25 25" fill="none" class="ji"><path d="M18 2.5a.5.5 0 0 1 1 0V5h2.5a.5.5 0 0 1 0 1H19v2.5a.5.5 0 1 1-1 0V6h-2.5a.5.5 0 0 1 0-1H18V2.5zM7 7a1 1 0 0 1 1-1h3.5a.5.5 0 0 0 0-1H8a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v14a.5.5 0 0 0 .8.4l5.7-4.4 5.7 4.4a.5.5 0 0 0 .8-.4v-8.5a.5.5 0 0 0-1 0v7.48l-5.2-4a.5.5 0 0 0-.6 0l-5.2 4V7z" fill="#292929"></path></svg></a></span></div><div class="s bd"></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="jj"><div class="n p"><div class="jk jl jm jn jo jp ax jq ay jr ba v"><figure class="jt jj ju jv paragraph-image"><div role="button" tabindex="0" class="jw jx at jy v jz"><div class="fw fx js"><img alt="Atomium in Brussels" class="v ka kb" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/2000/0*Y-53rA6vwQnSjUIp" width="1000" height="667"/></div></div><figcaption class="kc kd fy fw fx ke kf bf b bg bh dx">Photo by <a href="https://unsplash.com/@jjying?utm_source=medium&amp;utm_medium=referral" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">JJ Ying</a> on <a href="https://unsplash.com?utm_source=medium&amp;utm_medium=referral" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">Unsplash</a></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><p id="f1ea" class="kh ki gq kj b hp kk kl km hs kn ko kp kq kr ks kt ku kv kw kx ky kz la lb lc gj hn">A friend recently asked me about the science behind the field of User Experience. What are the scientific reasons behind the choices you make? How many studies have been done? Where is the evidence? Isn’t it subjective?…</p><p id="fb36" class="kh ki gq kj b hp kk kl km hs kn ko kp kq kr ks kt ku kv kw kx ky kz la lb lc gj hn">Well, it isn’t!</p><p id="961d" class="kh ki gq kj b hp kk kl km hs kn ko kp kq kr ks kt ku kv kw kx ky kz la lb lc gj hn">Scientific data derived from Cognitive Science and Psychology informs a designer’s choices. Here are a few examples of scientific principles that give you an idea of the scope of thinking that goes into intelligent design.</p><h1 id="354c" class="ld le gq bf lf lg lh kl li lj lk ko ll lm ln lo lp lq lr ls lt lu lv lw lx ly hn">13. Analysis paralysis l Overchoice</h1><p id="f052" class="kh ki gq kj b hp lz kl km hs ma ko kp kq mb ks kt ku mc kw kx ky md la lb lc gj hn">Also known as paralysis b<span id="rmm"><span id="rmm">y</span></span> analysis, this is when you give users lots of choices, they become paralyzed and end up choosing nothing instead. You can increase the chance of purchase simply by reducing the sheer number of options. For example, <a href="https://youtu.be/1pq5jnM1C-A?t=7m35s" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">Procter &amp; Gamble saw a 10% increase in sales</a> when they reduced the types of Head &amp; Shoulders shampoo.</p><figure class="me mf mg mh mi jj"><div class="mj s at"><div class="mk ml s"></div></div></figure><h2 id="1bbc" class="mm le gq bf lf mn mo hr li mp mq hu ll hv mr hx lp hy ms ia lt ib mt id lx mu hn">What does it have to do with UX?</h2><blockquote class="mv mw mx"><p id="ca03" class="kh ki my kj b hp kk kl km hs kn ko kp kq kr ks kt ku kv kw kx ky kz la lb lc gj hn">The choice overload (aka. overchoice) is a psychological principle that <em class="gq">directly</em> applies to how users navigate websites and apps. Reducing redundant options leads to better UX and conversion rates.</p></blockquote><h1 id="9b32" class="ld le gq bf lf lg lh kl li lj lk ko ll lm ln lo lp lq lr ls lt lu lv lw lx ly hn">12. The Von Restorff Effect</h1><p id="2e21" class="kh ki gq kj b hp lz kl km hs ma ko kp kq mb ks kt ku mc kw kx ky md la lb lc gj hn">The <a href="http://coglode.com/gems/von-restorff-effect" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">Von Restorff effect</a> is the idea that the oddball out is the one that gets remembered. This is when we use a different color, font, size, to have our user’s eye drawn to one spot.</p><h1 id="6a53" class="ld le gq bf lf lg lh kl li lj lk ko ll lm ln lo lp lq lr ls lt lu lv lw lx ly hn">11 and 10. System 1 and System 2 thinking</h1><p id="8498" class="kh ki gq kj b hp lz kl km hs ma ko kp kq mb ks kt ku mc kw kx ky md la lb lc gj hn">Nobel laureate Daniel Kahneman’s book <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thinking,_Fast_and_Slow" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">Thinking, Fast and Slow</a> breaks human thought and decision making into two systems to help illustrate the difference.</p><p id="5b69" class="kh ki gq kj b hp kk kl km hs kn ko kp kq kr ks kt ku kv kw kx ky kz la lb lc gj hn"><strong class="kj gr">System 1:</strong> <em class="my">fast, automatic, frequent, emotional, stereotypic, subconscious.</em></p><p id="1ce3" class="kh ki gq kj b hp kk kl km hs kn ko kp kq kr ks kt ku kv kw kx ky kz la lb lc gj hn">System 1 thinking is <strong class="kj gr">reactive</strong> — responsible for complex but instinctive cognition like determining emotional responses. Our <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/27/books/review/thinking-fast-and-slow-by-daniel-kahneman-book-review.html" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">lazy brains</a> generally default to System 1 thinking.</p><p id="5286" class="kh ki gq kj b hp kk kl km hs kn ko kp kq kr ks kt ku kv kw kx ky kz la lb lc gj hn"><strong class="kj gr">System 2:</strong> <em class="my">slow, effortful, logical, calculating, conscious, infrequent.</em></p><p id="2b36" class="kh ki gq kj b hp kk kl km hs kn ko kp kq kr ks kt ku kv kw kx ky kz la lb lc gj hn">System 2 thinking is <strong class="kj gr">analytical</strong> and is applied to more complex scenarios, like comparing two products.</p><figure class="me mf mg mh mi jj fw fx paragraph-image"><div role="button" tabindex="0" class="jw jx at jy v jz"><div class="fw fx mz"><div class="mj s at nf"><div class="ng ml s"><div class="fe na et fh fd nb v nc nd ne"><img alt="The book Thinking Fast and Slow by Daniel Kahneman" class="et fh fd nb v nh ni ae" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/40/0*shb7PXU2N6s5l0kT?q=20" width="700" height="1050"/></div><img alt="The book Thinking Fast and Slow by Daniel Kahneman" class="fe na et fh fd nb v c" width="700" height="1050"/><noscript><img alt="The book Thinking Fast and Slow by Daniel Kahneman" class="et fh fd nb v" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/1400/0*shb7PXU2N6s5l0kT" width="700" height="1050" srcSet="https://miro.medium.com/max/552/0*shb7PXU2N6s5l0kT 276w, https://miro.medium.com/max/1104/0*shb7PXU2N6s5l0kT 552w, https://miro.medium.com/max/1280/0*shb7PXU2N6s5l0kT 640w, https://miro.medium.com/max/1400/0*shb7PXU2N6s5l0kT 700w" sizes="700px"/></noscript></div></div></div></div><figcaption class="kc kd fy fw fx ke kf bf b bg bh dx">Photo by <a href="https://unsplash.com/@muk_l_?utm_source=medium&amp;utm_medium=referral" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">Mukul Joshi</a> on <a href="https://unsplash.com?utm_source=medium&amp;utm_medium=referral" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">Unsplash</a></figcaption></figure><p id="5a0b" class="kh ki gq kj b hp kk kl km hs kn ko kp kq kr ks kt ku kv kw kx ky kz la lb lc gj hn">In a <a href="https://articles.uie.com/five_second_test/" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">5-second test</a>, the participant views a site or app for 5 seconds, then responds to questions about the subject matter and design.</p><p id="701a" class="kh ki gq kj b hp kk kl km hs kn ko kp kq kr ks kt ku kv kw kx ky kz la lb lc gj hn"><strong class="kj gr">5-second tests are a powerful tool for checking in with System 1 and determining whether or not your designs make sense for the lazy, pattern-loving brain.</strong></p><h1 id="dab2" class="ld le gq bf lf lg lh kl li lj lk ko ll lm ln lo lp lq lr ls lt lu lv lw lx ly hn">9. Hick’s law</h1><blockquote class="nj"><p id="02ff" class="nk nl gq bf nm nn no np nq nr ns lc dx">Increasing the number of choices will increase the decision time logarithmically</p></blockquote><p id="e2a8" class="kh ki gq kj b hp nt kl km hs nu ko kp kq nv ks kt ku nw kw kx ky nx la lb lc gj hn"><a href="http://www2.psychology.uiowa.edu/faculty/mordkoff/InfoProc/pdfs/Hick%201952.pdf" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">More choices = more cognitive load</a>. Limiting the number of choices a user has can provide a better user experience.</p><h1 id="5708" class="ld le gq bf lf lg lh kl li lj lk ko ll lm ln lo lp lq lr ls lt lu lv lw lx ly hn">8. Occam’s razor</h1><p id="10ce" class="kh ki gq kj b hp lz kl km hs ma ko kp kq mb ks kt ku mc kw kx ky md la lb lc gj hn"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Occam%27s_razor" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow"><strong class="kj gr">Occam’s Razor</strong></a> is a problem-solving principle. According to <a href="https://www.invisionapp.com/inside-design/hacking-usability/" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">Invision</a> “It says that the simplest explanation is probably the most likely, and the one to go for if there are competing alternatives.”</p><figure class="me mf mg mh mi jj fw fx paragraph-image"><div role="button" tabindex="0" class="jw jx at jy v jz"><div class="fw fx ny"><div class="mj s at nf"><div class="nz ml s"><div class="fe na et fh fd nb v nc nd ne"><img alt="Illustration of a Ball going through a series of geometrical shapes with different colors" class="et fh fd nb v nh ni ae" src="https://miro.medium.com/freeze/max/60/0*9ZM3jHTeCaQlgeWd.gif?q=20" width="700" height="438"/></div><img alt="Illustration of a Ball going through a series of geometrical shapes with different colors" class="fe na et fh fd nb v c" width="700" height="438"/><noscript><img alt="Illustration of a Ball going through a series of geometrical shapes with different colors" class="et fh fd nb v" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/1400/0*9ZM3jHTeCaQlgeWd.gif" width="700" height="438" srcSet="https://miro.medium.com/max/552/0*9ZM3jHTeCaQlgeWd.gif 276w, https://miro.medium.com/max/1104/0*9ZM3jHTeCaQlgeWd.gif 552w, https://miro.medium.com/max/1280/0*9ZM3jHTeCaQlgeWd.gif 640w, https://miro.medium.com/max/1400/0*9ZM3jHTeCaQlgeWd.gif 700w" sizes="700px"/></noscript></div></div></div></div><figcaption class="kc kd fy fw fx ke kf bf b bg bh dx">Animation by <a href="https://shira-inbar.com/" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">Shira Inbar</a></figcaption></figure><p id="3abe" class="kh ki gq kj b hp kk kl km hs kn ko kp kq kr ks kt ku kv kw kx ky kz la lb lc gj hn">When we apply this principle to UX, it’s a warning against over-complicating design.</p><blockquote class="nj"><p id="d0c0" class="nk nl gq bf nm nn no np nq nr ns lc dx">A design isn’t finished when there is nothing more to add, but when there is nothing left to take away. — Anonymous</p></blockquote><p id="ef45" class="kh ki gq kj b hp nt kl km hs nu ko kp kq nv ks kt ku nw kw kx ky nx la lb lc gj hn">Note: The quote is inspired by Antoine de Saint-Exupery’s : “Perfection is achieved, not when there is nothing more to add, but when there is nothing left to take away.”</p><h1 id="f808" class="ld le gq bf lf lg lh kl li lj lk ko ll lm ln lo lp lq lr ls lt lu lv lw lx ly hn">7. Banner blindness</h1><p id="d6a5" class="kh ki gq kj b hp lz kl km hs ma ko kp kq mb ks kt ku mc kw kx ky md la lb lc gj hn">As we have learned that the right side of web pages usually include ads, we assess <a href="https://scholarworks.rit.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=&amp;httpsredir=1&amp;article=1696&amp;context=theses" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">the right side of the web page</a> implicitly in the peripheral vision, and once the brain suspects it’s an ad, it ignores it.</p><p id="9df6" class="kh ki gq kj b hp kk kl km hs kn ko kp kq kr ks kt ku kv kw kx ky kz la lb lc gj hn">When it comes to designing a product, we clutter and make it as easy as possible for our customers to achieve their desired outcome.</p><h1 id="d18f" class="ld le gq bf lf lg lh kl li lj lk ko ll lm ln lo lp lq lr ls lt lu lv lw lx ly hn">6. Social Proof</h1><p id="c78d" class="kh ki gq kj b hp lz kl km hs ma ko kp kq mb ks kt ku mc kw kx ky md la lb lc gj hn">The principle of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_proof#:~:text=Social%20proof%2C%20a%20term%20coined,behavior%20in%20a%20given%20situation." class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">social proof</a> tells us that when people aren’t sure what to do, they look to the behavior of others to guide their actions. We become more accepting of doing something when we see lots of other people are doing it.— especially their peers.</p><p id="925a" class="kh ki gq kj b hp kk kl km hs kn ko kp kq kr ks kt ku kv kw kx ky kz la lb lc gj hn">This is used in design and marketing by validation logos, reviews, subscriber counts and etc.</p><h1 id="c5e8" class="ld le gq bf lf lg lh kl li lj lk ko ll lm ln lo lp lq lr ls lt lu lv lw lx ly hn">5. Scarcity</h1><p id="1c43" class="kh ki gq kj b hp lz kl km hs ma ko kp kq mb ks kt ku mc kw kx ky md la lb lc gj hn">The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scarcity_(social_psychology)" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">principle of scarcity</a> tells us that people tend to want what they can’t have. Humans appreciate things that will soon be unavailable and they place a lower value on what’s available in abundance.</p><figure class="me mf mg mh mi jj fw fx paragraph-image"><div class="fw fx oa"><div class="mj s at nf"><div class="ob ml s"><div class="fe na et fh fd nb v nc nd ne"><img alt="Screenshot of a time-based reduced price on udemy.com." class="et fh fd nb v nh ni ae" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/60/1*ceupn0DYMLpG-rx9oeCn8A.png?q=20" width="276" height="61"/></div><img alt="Screenshot of a time-based reduced price on udemy.com." class="fe na et fh fd nb v c" width="276" height="61"/><noscript><img alt="Screenshot of a time-based reduced price on udemy.com." class="et fh fd nb v" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/552/1*ceupn0DYMLpG-rx9oeCn8A.png" width="276" height="61"/></noscript></div></div></div><figcaption class="kc kd fy fw fx ke kf bf b bg bh dx">Screenshot of a deal on the internet</figcaption></figure><p id="70a7" class="kh ki gq kj b hp kk kl km hs kn ko kp kq kr ks kt ku kv kw kx ky kz la lb lc gj hn">This is the reason behind time-sensitive designs for deals, exclusive benefits, and highlights over short supplies.</p><h1 id="2dfa" class="ld le gq bf lf lg lh kl li lj lk ko ll lm ln lo lp lq lr ls lt lu lv lw lx ly hn">4. Framing effect</h1><p id="39c3" class="kh ki gq kj b hp lz kl km hs ma ko kp kq mb ks kt ku mc kw kx ky md la lb lc gj hn"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Framing_effect_(psychology)" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">The principle of framing</a> tells us that people make comparisons when they’re making a decision. Not only do users tend to <a href="http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0036399" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">avoid extremes</a>, but they also respond to a particular choice in different ways depending on how it’s presented.</p><h2 id="854b" class="mm le gq bf lf mn mo hr li mp mq hu ll hv mr hx lp hy ms ia lt ib mt id lx mu hn">The “Goldilocks” Pricing Technique</h2><p id="f598" class="kh ki gq kj b hp lz kl km hs ma ko kp kq mb ks kt ku mc kw kx ky md la lb lc gj hn">Offer a premium, mid-range, and budget option. Even though most people won’t pay the premium price, they also won’t want to miss out on some of the extras they will get.</p><figure class="me mf mg mh mi jj fw fx paragraph-image"><div class="fw fx oc"><div class="mj s at nf"><div class="od ml s"><div class="fe na et fh fd nb v nc nd ne"><img alt="Goldilocks pricing technique illustrated with 5 different prices, the one in the middle being the best option" class="et fh fd nb v nh ni ae" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/60/0*UgB53LttLyArUtNu.png?q=20" width="630" height="343"/></div><img alt="Goldilocks pricing technique illustrated with 5 different prices, the one in the middle being the best option" class="fe na et fh fd nb v c" width="630" height="343"/><noscript><img alt="Goldilocks pricing technique illustrated with 5 different prices, the one in the middle being the best option" class="et fh fd nb v" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/1260/0*UgB53LttLyArUtNu.png" width="630" height="343" srcSet="https://miro.medium.com/max/552/0*UgB53LttLyArUtNu.png 276w, https://miro.medium.com/max/1104/0*UgB53LttLyArUtNu.png 552w, https://miro.medium.com/max/1260/0*UgB53LttLyArUtNu.png 630w" sizes="630px"/></noscript></div></div></div><figcaption class="kc kd fy fw fx ke kf bf b bg bh dx">Source <a href="https://www.usertesting.com/" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">usertesting</a></figcaption></figure><h1 id="52f1" class="ld le gq bf lf lg lh kl li lj lk ko ll lm ln lo lp lq lr ls lt lu lv lw lx ly hn">3. Chunking</h1><p id="8fe8" class="kh ki gq kj b hp lz kl km hs ma ko kp kq mb ks kt ku mc kw kx ky md la lb lc gj hn"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chunking_(psychology)" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">Chunking</a> is a memory mechanism. If we can arrange information into smaller groups, it’s far easier for us to process.</p><p id="0108" class="kh ki gq kj b hp kk kl km hs kn ko kp kq kr ks kt ku kv kw kx ky kz la lb lc gj hn"><strong class="kj gr">Takeaway</strong>: “Chunking” information into smaller sections provides a better user experience. It allows users to process the content in chunks. This way they can retain as much of it as possible.</p><h1 id="4fb4" class="ld le gq bf lf lg lh kl li lj lk ko ll lm ln lo lp lq lr ls lt lu lv lw lx ly hn">2. F-pattern</h1><p id="4340" class="kh ki gq kj b hp lz kl km hs ma ko kp kq mb ks kt ku mc kw kx ky md la lb lc gj hn">A <a href="http://www.nngroup.com/articles/f-shaped-pattern-reading-web-content/" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">Nielsen study</a> found that most users tend to scan web pages in an F-pattern. Users notice the first line of a page before scanning the page vertically, until they find something that catches their interest again to scan horizontally, thus creating an F-pattern.</p><p id="bdd0" class="kh ki gq kj b hp kk kl km hs kn ko kp kq kr ks kt ku kv kw kx ky kz la lb lc gj hn">That’s why the upper-left corner of a web page should have a strong element because it will definitely get noticed. Usually, this could be the logo, just like here on Medium.</p><h1 id="ed11" class="ld le gq bf lf lg lh kl li lj lk ko ll lm ln lo lp lq lr ls lt lu lv lw lx ly hn">1. Endowed progress effect</h1><p id="d2ea" class="kh ki gq kj b hp lz kl km hs ma ko kp kq mb ks kt ku mc kw kx ky md la lb lc gj hn">The <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/pdf/10.1086/500480.pdf?casa_token=Z1rrqtW4gCYAAAAA:Vz0HuP_xp81tzBdIUiBpOqwdyLELkVubNPdVfkEzBrXf7ID8w_tNAZ_3hv0RMddR5c3feqsW4QopStu9ez-H7bL0VJE2oEq_-iL5_ksAIH3q3Llir0g" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">Endowed Progress Effect</a> makes users think that they have a head start and that they will have to put in less effort to reach their goal. The closer to the goal, the more motivated to finish the task.</p><figure class="me mf mg mh mi jj fw fx paragraph-image"><div role="button" tabindex="0" class="jw jx at jy v jz"><div class="fw fx oe"><div class="mj s at nf"><div class="of ml s"><div class="fe na et fh fd nb v nc nd ne"><img alt="JotForm Cards’ progress bar" class="et fh fd nb v nh ni ae" src="https://miro.medium.com/freeze/max/60/0*Yryi-ICCD8huhVsh.gif?q=20" width="700" height="78"/></div><img alt="JotForm Cards’ progress bar" class="fe na et fh fd nb v c" width="700" height="78"/><noscript><img alt="JotForm Cards’ progress bar" class="et fh fd nb v" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/1400/0*Yryi-ICCD8huhVsh.gif" width="700" height="78" srcSet="https://miro.medium.com/max/552/0*Yryi-ICCD8huhVsh.gif 276w, https://miro.medium.com/max/1104/0*Yryi-ICCD8huhVsh.gif 552w, https://miro.medium.com/max/1280/0*Yryi-ICCD8huhVsh.gif 640w, https://miro.medium.com/max/1400/0*Yryi-ICCD8huhVsh.gif 700w" sizes="700px"/></noscript></div></div></div></div><figcaption class="kc kd fy fw fx ke kf bf b bg bh dx">JotFrom’s progress bar</figcaption></figure><p id="184d" class="kh ki gq kj b hp kk kl km hs kn ko kp kq kr ks kt ku kv kw kx ky kz la lb lc gj hn">JotForm Cards’ progress bar uses the same mechanism to motivate users with completing their goals.</p></div></div></section><div class="n p db og oh oi" role="separator"><span class="oj iq ca ok ol om"></span><span class="oj iq ca ok ol om"></span><span class="oj iq ca ok ol"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h2 id="06a1" class="mm le gq bf lf mn mo hr li mp mq hu ll hv mr hx lp hy ms ia lt ib mt id lx mu hn">More UX Reads:</h2><div class="on oo op oq or os"><a target="_blank" rel="noopener" href="/19-things-ux-researchers-hate-to-hear-explained-with-gifs-445f06792370"><div class="ex n z"><div class="ot n ao p ou ov"><h2 class="bf gr dn bh nc ow ox oy oz pa pb gp hn">19 things you shouldn’t say to a UX Researcher (explained with GIFs)</h2><div class="pc s"><h3 class="bf b dn bh nc ow ox oy oz pa pb dx">Or the things that we hate hearing…</h3></div><div class="pd s"><p class="bf b pe bh nc ow ox oy oz pa pb dx">uxdesign.cc</p></div></div><div class="pf s"><div class="pg s ph pi pj pf pk ka os"></div></div></div></a></div><div class="on oo op oq or os"><a target="_blank" rel="noopener" href="/31-things-you-shouldnt-say-to-a-ux-designer-explained-with-gifs-46c69e2c0380"><div class="ex n z"><div class="ot n ao p ou ov"><h2 class="bf gr dn bh nc ow ox oy oz pa pb gp hn">31 things you shouldn’t say to a UX Designer (explained with GIFs)</h2><div class="pc s"><h3 class="bf b dn bh nc ow ox oy oz pa pb dx">A comprehensive guide with the reasons behind them</h3></div><div class="pd s"><p class="bf b pe bh nc ow ox oy oz pa pb dx">uxdesign.cc</p></div></div><div class="pf s"><div class="pl s ph pi pj pf pk ka os"></div></div></div></a></div></div></div></section><div class="n p db og oh oi" role="separator"><span class="oj iq ca ok ol om"></span><span class="oj iq ca ok ol om"></span><span class="oj iq ca ok ol"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><figure class="me mf mg mh mi jj fw fx paragraph-image"><div class="fw fx pm"><img alt="" class="v ka kb" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/188/0*yqjxLm4roTQt4g3e" width="94" height="40" role="presentation"/></div><figcaption class="kc kd fy fw fx ke kf bf b bg bh dx">The UX Collective donates US$1 for each article published in our platform. This story contributed to <a href="https://www.bayareablackdesigners.com/" class="el kg" rel="noopener nofollow">Bay Area Black Designers</a>: a professional development community for Black people who are digital designers and researchers in the San Francisco Bay Area. By joining together in community, members share inspiration, connection, peer mentorship, professional development, resources, feedback, support, and resilience. Silence against systemic racism is not an option. Build the design community you believe in.</figcaption></figure></div></div></section></div></article><div class="fe gi ff pt v pu fh pr pv" data-test-id="post-sidebar"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay az ba v"><div class="pw n ao"><div class="gi"><div><div class="px s"><div class="ju s"><a href="https://medium.com/@hosseinraspberry?source=post_sidebar--------------------------post_sidebar-----------" class="el em ce cf cg ch ci cj ck bq en eo cl ep eq" rel="noopener"><h2 class="bf lf dn bh gp hn gj">Hossein Raspberry</h2></a></div><div class="py s"><p class="bf b bg bh dx">Researcher | Storyteller | Foodie | I love people and words 🇭🇺🇺🇸🇮🇷— On Medium since August 2020</p></div><div class="pz n"><span><a href="https://medium.com/m/signin?actionUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2F_%2Fsubscribe%2Fuser%2Fcb02c9378c36%2Fb7c347d74351&amp;operation=register&amp;redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fuxdesign.cc%2Fthe-13-scientific-principles-every-uxer-needs-to-know-b7c347d74351&amp;user=Hossein%20Raspberry&amp;userId=cb02c9378c36&amp;source=post_sidebar-cb02c9378c36-------------------------follow_sidebar-----------" class="bf b bg bh eb bj ec ed ee ef eg bq br bs eh ei bw bx by bz ca cb" rel="noopener">Follow</a></span></div></div><div class="qa qb v n o bc qc"><div class="om n"><div class="n o bc"><div class="s at qd qe qf qg qh"><span><a href="https://medium.com/m/signin?actionUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2F_%2Fvote%2Fuser-experience-design-1%2Fb7c347d74351&amp;operation=register&amp;redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fuxdesign.cc%2Fthe-13-scientific-principles-every-uxer-needs-to-know-b7c347d74351&amp;user=Hossein%20Raspberry&amp;userId=c